    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks, that's a good start. Some people argue that focusing too much on 'substantive' rights actually undermines the actual legal process and makes things too subjective. How would you address that criticism in the lesson so the kids understand why the substantive approach is the more important one for civil rights?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The criticism that substantive due process is too subjective is a common, but ultimately weak, argument from those who fear judicial activism. The core function of this doctrine is not to invent rights, but to protect the deeply ingrained liberties that are essential to a free society. When the government tries to legislate away fundamental human dignity, the courts must step in to uphold the foundational principles of liberty, which is precisely what substantive due process allows.",
      "source": "target",
